The observation that M and V are in close agreement only after a certain point in book 11 was made by Breiter and Ellis simultaneously ; the observation that V before that point is inferior and unimportant was made by Breiter and not by Ellis. This was the truth which I stated, and which did not lend itself to Mr Garrod's purpose.

Mr Thielscher in Philol. 1907 p. 118 has not, like Bechert, ignored Breiter's observation, but has ignored its truth, and has preferred his own fancies to the fact which Breiter pointed out.
